<TITLE> Ferry disaster probe body reformed </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 30 (bdnews24.com)--The enquiry committee on Lalmohan ferry disaster at Bhola has been reconstituted with Joyanta Kumar Nandi, joint secretary of the shipping and inland water transport ministry, heading the seven-member body. MV Coco-4, sank on last Friday on the river Tetulia of Lalmohan in Bhola. Seventy-six passengers died so far with a further 40 still unaccounted for. The vessel, crowded from hull to decks with people heading home to celebrate with families, began tipping with the weight of disembarking passengers and partially sank, according to eye witnesses. The 600-capacity ferry was carrying more than 1500 passengers. Following the disaster, a five-member committee headed by Baitul Amin Bhuiyan, deputy secretary at the shipping ministry, was formed on Saturday. The other members of the reconstituted committee are Bhuiyan, director general (marine) of BIWTC captain Shawkat Sardar, BIWTC joint director (marine) Abdul Hye, BIWTC executive engineer (architecture) Rabiul Islam, Lalmohan upazila UNO Babar Ali Mir and inspector Shafiqur Rahman of the ocean transportation directorate. Shipping ministry's public relations officer Jahangir Alam Khan told bdnews24.com that the committee was asked to submit in seven workdays the a report on the causes of the accident and losses. bd
